%N A151543 Smallest precursor of n-th cycle in the "Recurring Digital Invariant Variant" problem.
%C A151543 The problem is the following:
%C A151543 a) choose a number N
%C A151543 b) let k be the number of digits in N
%C A151543 c) raise each digit of N to the k-th power and add the results
%C A151543 d) call the new number N and repeat
%C A151543 Example:
%C A151543 a) 14 = N
%C A151543 b) k = 2
%C A151543 c) 1^2 + 4^2 = 17
%C A151543 d) 17 = N
%C A151543 e) k = 2
%C A151543 f) 1^2 + 7^2 = 50
%C A151543 g) 50 = N
%C A151543 ... etc.
%C A151543 Here is the trajectory of 14:
%C A151543 14 -> 1^2 + 4^2 = 17
%C A151543 17 -> 1^2 + 7^2 = 50
%C A151543 50 -> 5^2 + 0^2 = 25
%C A151543 25 -> 2^2 + 5^2 = 29
%C A151543 29 -> 2^2 + 9^2 = 85
%C A151543 85 -> 8^2 + 5^2 = 89
%C A151543 89 -> 8^2 + 9^2 = 145
%C A151543 145 -> 1^3 + 4^3 + 5^3 = 190
%C A151543 190 -> 1^3 + 9^3 + 0^3 = 730
%C A151543 730 -> 7^3 + 3^3 + 0^3 = 370
%C A151543 370 -> 3^3 + 7^3 + 0^3 = 370 (fixed point)
%C A151543 The question is, what are the cycles that appear in the trajectories?
